<font color="#FF0000">LET'S GET THINGS STRAIGHT!</font><br>
<tt>Tue Mar  4  1:00:51 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Jeffrey,<br>
     I don't know how old you are, but you evidently don't have the foggiest idea what went on in this country in the late '40's.  Attempted and sometiimes successful espionage by the American Communist Party from the '30's on up is well documented by the files relating to the theft of A-bomb secrets to recently declassified US material that's passed the 50 year holding point to recently released corroborative material from Russia.  Yes, many became Communists during the '30's because they despaired of anything else bringing justice to the workingman, but Uncle Joe called the tune.  Everytime the party line changed in the Soviet Union, the American Communist Party dutifully followed suit.<br><br>
I don't appreciate my mother and father being called liars; because that's what you're doing.  My father was the type of ward committeeman that held elctions sacred and never fixed a ticket in 16 years of service.  I've met few people with his standards of integrity.  You were not there, and eveidently are so hung up on the left being the only good guys that you can't believe what I'm posting.  My mother wouldn't be amused by the thought of no threat. How would you like it if your family and home were watched all day by strange men?  <br><br>
I don't appreciate my words being twisted.  It's not something I'm used to.  I personally don't see Communists under every bed. I didn't say so.  I don't believe Communists controled Hollywood, ever.  But the attempt to infiltrate the industrial unions in the '40's was very real.  Where did you learn your history?  As for Sen. Joseph McCarthy; my father opposed him from the beginning, and in that I still believe he was right.  There is a world of difference in labeling innocent people &quot;Communists&quot;, and recognizing that there were some real and dangerous ones out there.  The men that ordered the tanks into Hungary in 1956 and ended the Prague Spring with the same were not figments of the world's imagination.  Neither are the people who executed thousands of their defeated enemies in Vietnam in 1975.  The defeated shed blood just as real as that of the villagers of My Lai.  As I said there were some real reasons for being scared. Remember Krushchev: &quot;We will bury you&quot;. You think he was playing?<br><br>
I hope this isn't just some intellectual game with you; because there are too many people out there coming into these sights with non-physical wounds from the Vietnam War. And they are not all vets.  I know well that some were and still are protesters.<br><br>
And also please be more careful of your terms.  Considering the Soviet Union planned spy sattelites from the beginning and had several different spy networks in place; the U-2 flights were basically the same thing by another means.  Provocation, yes.  Act of War, quite debatable under the circumstances.<br><br>
Let me ask you bluntly.  Are you at the point where you believe everything thing your own country did was wrong, and everybody else is innocent?  I've seen enough in 52 years to know this country makes mistakes, some of them horrendous<br>
(trying to &quot;civilize&quot; Native Americans), and occasionally acts from less than honorable motives; as in the WWII Japanese internment.  Yet there is no country on the face of the earth that tries harder to become better than it is.  Every power on this planet has its My Lai's, and some quite a few.  We're the only ones that ever put anyone on trial; as imperfect as that process was.  Even a place like New Zealand has its skeletons in the closet (the Maoris).  I won't even deny that we played power politics a la Bismark in our handling of Ceausescu; though most of what is known about the depths of his infamy is after the fact.  It's easy to hit a target with 20-20 hindsight.<br><br>
Again, playing clever with someone's personal history; because it is outside your own experience shows either cruelty or unwillingness to accept the other party is telling the truth till proven otherwise.  Your choice.  I stand by my parents.  Whatever problems I've had with them, lying was NEVER one. <br>

<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney) </code><p>


